      <h2>What Is Base64 Encoding?</h2>

      <p>Base64 encoding converts arbitrary binary data into a string of ASCII characters using a 64-character alphabet (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /), with = for padding. It was designed to transport binary data through text-only channels like email (MIME), XML, and JSON. Every 3 bytes of input become 4 characters of output, resulting in a consistent ~33% size increase.</p>

      <p>Common use cases include embedding images in HTML/CSS via data URIs (<code>data:image/png;base64,...</code>), encoding binary attachments in email (MIME), transmitting binary data in JSON API payloads, storing binary data in text-only databases, and encoding credentials in HTTP Basic Authentication headers.</p>

      <h2>What Is URL Encoding?</h2>

      <p>URL encoding (percent-encoding) replaces unsafe characters in URLs with a percent sign followed by two hex digits representing the character's ASCII code. For example, a space becomes <code>%20</code>, an ampersand becomes <code>%26</code>, and a forward slash becomes <code>%2F</code>. Characters that are "unreserved" (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, -, _, ., ~) are left unchanged.</p>

      <p>URL encoding is required whenever you include user input in query parameters (<code>?search=hello%20world</code>), form data submitted via GET or POST (<code>application/x-www-form-urlencoded</code>), path segments containing special characters, and fragment identifiers with non-ASCII characters.</p>

      <h2>Key Differences Explained</h2>

      <h3>1. Purpose: Binary Transport vs URL Safety</h3>
      <p>Base64 solves the problem of moving binary data (images, files, encrypted blobs) through text-only channels. URL encoding solves the problem of including special characters in URLs without breaking the URL structure. They solve completely different problems.</p>

      <h3>2. Size Impact</h3>
      <p>Base64 always adds exactly 33% overhead regardless of input content. URL encoding's overhead varies wildly: plain ASCII text passes through with zero overhead, but CJK characters or binary data can triple or quadruple in size because each byte becomes a 3-character <code>%XX</code> sequence.</p>

      <h3>3. Common Mistake: Double Encoding</h3>
      <p>A frequent bug is Base64-encoding data and then URL-encoding the result (or vice versa). This produces garbled output. If you need to include Base64 data in a URL, use Base64URL encoding (RFC 4648 §5), which replaces <code>+</code> with <code>-</code> and <code>/</code> with <code>_</code>, and omits padding — making the output URL-safe without additional percent-encoding.</p>

      <h2>When to Use Each</h2>

      <h3>Use Base64 When:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Embedding binary data (images, fonts) in HTML/CSS</li>
        <li>Sending binary payloads through JSON APIs</li>
        <li>Encoding email attachments (MIME)</li>
        <li>Storing binary data in text fields (databases, config files)</li>
        <li>HTTP Basic Authentication (<code>Authorization: Basic base64(user:pass)</code>)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Use URL Encoding When:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Building query strings with user input</li>
        <li>Submitting HTML forms via GET</li>
        <li>Constructing redirect URLs with parameters</li>
        <li>Including special characters in REST API paths</li>
        <li>Encoding non-ASCII characters in URLs (internationalized domain names)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>

      <h3>Can I use Base64 in URLs?</h3>
      <p>Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>=</code>, which have special meaning in URLs. Use Base64URL encoding instead, which substitutes these characters with URL-safe alternatives (<code>-</code>, <code>_</code>, no padding).</p>

      <h3>Is Base64 encryption?</h3>
      <p>No. Base64 is encoding, not encryption. It provides zero security — anyone can decode it instantly. Never use Base64 to "hide" sensitive data like passwords or API keys.</p>

      <h3>Does URL encoding handle Unicode?</h3>
      <p>Yes. JavaScript's <code>encodeURIComponent()</code> first converts the string to UTF-8 bytes, then percent-encodes each byte. So the emoji "😀" becomes <code>%F0%9F%98%80</code> (4 UTF-8 bytes, each percent-encoded).</p>

